(43, 6, 11, 44, 27, 35, 35, NULL, 'Thanksgiving and Breaking Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving thanks before breaking bread. This connection highlights the communal aspect of sharing food in the presence of others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 42, 1, 53, 53, 'filled, he said unto his disciples', 'Connection of Fulfillment and Hunger', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfillment, as both passages address the filling of the hungry. John 6:12 speaks of gathering fragments after feeding the multitude, while Luke 1:53 mentions filling the hungry with good things.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 16, 8, 10, 10, 'that nothing be lost', 'Gathering and Sharing Provisions', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering and sharing resources. Both passages emphasize the importance of ensuring that nothing is lost or wasted, as seen in the directive to ''gather up the fragments'' and to ''send portions unto them for whom nothing is prepared.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 16, 9, 25, 25, 'that nothing be lost', 'Connection of Abundance and Preservation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being filled and the importance of gathering what remains. In John, the instruction to gather fragments reflects a care for abundance, similar to Nehemiah''s description of a land filled with goods.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 40, 15, 37, 38, 'Gather up the fragments that remain', 'Gathering of Fragments', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of leftover food after a miraculous feeding. In John, Jesus instructs to ''Gather up the fragments that remain,'' while Matthew describes the collection of ''broken meat that was left.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 41, 6, 42, 44, 'Gather up the fragments that remain', 'Connection of Fragment Gathering', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of fragments after the feeding of the multitude, highlighting the importance of not wasting food. The act of collecting leftovers signifies abundance and care in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 42, 9, 17, 17, 'Gather up the fragments that remain', 'Connection of Fragment Gathering', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of fragments after the meal, highlighting the importance of not wasting food. The act of collecting leftovers serves as a reminder of abundance and care in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 12, 20, 18, 9, 9, 'that nothing be lost', 'Wastefulness and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the importance of not wasting resources. In John 6:12, the instruction to gather up fragments reflects a responsibility to avoid waste, which parallels Proverbs 18:9''s warning against slothfulness and wastefulness in work.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 20, 11, 24, 25, 'twelve baskets with the fragments', 'Connection of Generosity and Abundance', 'This connection highlights the theme of abundance resulting from generosity. In John 6:13, the fragments left over symbolize the increase that follows the sharing of resources, paralleling Proverbs 11:24-25, which emphasizes that scattering leads to increase.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 11, 7, 15, 16, 'twelve baskets', 'Connection of Numbers and Provision', 'Both passages emphasize the number twelve and the concept of abundance. In John 6:13, twelve baskets are filled with fragments, while in 1 Kings 7:15-16, two pillars are described with a measurement of twelve cubits. This connection highlights the significance of these numbers in relation to divine provision.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 12, 4, 2, 7, NULL, 'Miraculous Provision of Food', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of miraculous provision from limited resources. In John 6:13, the fragments from five loaves are gathered, while in 2 Kings 4:2-7, a small amount of oil is multiplied to meet needs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 14, 25, 9, 9, NULL, 'Divine Provision and Abundance', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s ability to provide abundantly. In John 6:13, the gathering of fragments signifies surplus from a small amount, while 2 Chronicles 25:9 emphasizes God''s capacity to give ''much more'' than what is initially given.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 47, 9, 8, 9, 'filled twelve baskets with the fragments', 'Abundance and Generosity', 'This connection highlights the theme of abundance in both passages. In John 6:13, the leftover fragments symbolize God''s provision, while 2 Corinthians 9:8-9 emphasizes God''s ability to provide sufficiency for good works, reflecting a similar generosity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 13, 50, 4, 19, 19, 'fragments of the five barley loaves', 'God''s Provision and Abundance', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s provision, as seen in the abundance of leftovers in John 6:13 and the assurance of supply in Philippians 4:19. Both passages emphasize that God meets needs abundantly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 5, 18, 15, 18, 'that prophet that should come', 'Prophetic Identity of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as the Prophet foretold in Deuteronomy. Both passages emphasize the role of a Prophet who speaks God''s words, with the crowd in John affirming Jesus'' identity as that Prophet.', 'prophecy', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'that prophet that should come', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as a prophet in both passages. In John 6:14, the crowd identifies Jesus as ''that prophet,'' while in Matthew 21:11, they refer to Him as ''the prophet of Nazareth.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 44, 7, 37, 37, 'that prophet that should come', 'Connection Between Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of a prophet. John 6:14 identifies Jesus as ''that prophet,'' while Acts 7:37 refers to Moses'' prophecy about a coming prophet. This connection highlights the continuity of prophetic expectation.', 'prophecy', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 40, 11, 3, 3, 'that prophet that should come', 'Recognition of the Prophet', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as ''that prophet'' who was expected to come. Both passages reflect the anticipation and inquiry regarding Jesus'' identity as the awaited figure.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 43, 1, 21, 21, 'that prophet', 'Recognition of the Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as ''that prophet.'' In John 6:14, the crowd identifies Jesus after witnessing a miracle, while in John 1:21, the question about ''that prophet'' indicates the expectation of a significant figure.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 43, 7, 40, 40, 'this is of a truth that prophet', 'Recognition of the Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as ''the Prophet'' following miraculous events. This connection highlights the people''s acknowledgment of Jesus'' significance in light of His works.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 14, 44, 3, 22, 24, 'that prophet that should come into the world', 'Connection Between Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a prophet raised by God. John 6:14 identifies Jesus as ''that prophet,'' while Acts 3:22-24 references Moses'' prophecy about a similar prophet. This connection highlights the continuity of prophetic expectation in the New Testament.', 'prophecy', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 43, 18, 36, 36, 'to make him a king', 'Jesus'' Kingdom Not of This World', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' rejection of worldly kingship. In both passages, Jesus distances himself from the idea of being made a king and emphasizes that his kingdom is not of this world.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 43, 6, 15, 21, 'he departed again into a mountain himself alone', 'Jesus'' Authority and Control', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' authority over both the crowd''s desire to make him king and the natural elements during the storm. Both passages emphasize his ability to navigate challenging situations, whether through retreating from the crowd or walking on water.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 42, 19, 38, 38, 'king', 'Connection of Kingship Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' kingship. In John 6:15, Jesus departs to avoid being made king by force, while in Luke 19:38, He is acknowledged as the King coming in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 41, 6, 45, 52, 'he departed again into a mountain', 'Jesus Retreats to Pray', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus departing into a mountain alone after a significant event. This connection highlights his need for solitude and prayer following the crowd''s desire to make him king.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 41, 11, 9, 9, 'make him a king', 'Jesus and Kingship', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' kingship. In John 6:15, the crowd seeks to make Jesus a king by force, while in Mark 11:9, the crowd acknowledges him with praise, declaring him blessed as he comes in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 40, 14, 22, 33, 'he departed again into a mountain himself alone', 'Jesus Retreats to Pray', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' retreat to a mountain alone after a significant event. In John, he departs to avoid being made king, while in Matthew, he goes to pray after sending away the multitudes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 15, 58, 4, 13, 13, 'perceived that they would come', 'Perception of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the awareness of Jesus'' authority and the perception of his role. In John, Jesus perceives the people''s intentions to make him king, while Hebrews emphasizes that all things are manifest in his sight, suggesting a deep understanding of human motives.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 17, 41, 6, 45, 45, 'entered into a ship', 'Disciples in a Ship', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples entering a ship to cross the sea. The mention of darkness in John highlights the uncertainty of their journey, while Mark indicates their departure before sending away the crowd.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 17, 43, 6, 24, 25, 'Capernaum', 'Seeking Jesus in Capernaum', 'Both passages emphasize the absence of Jesus and the disciples as the people seek him in Capernaum. The mention of Capernaum in both verses connects the narrative of the disciples'' journey and the crowd''s search for Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
